add("ITGC-AC-15","ITGC · Access","ITGC","All","A compromised or shared session cannot be terminated — a stolen/forwarded JWT stays valid for its full lifetime, and a deactivated user's existing token keeps working, so there is no incident-containment kill-switch.","Restricted access",
    "Session revocation: JWTs carry a jti so a session can be killed before expiry. Logout adds the token's jti to a denylist (revoked_tokens) which the global auth guard checks every request; an admin can revoke ALL of a user's sessions (users.tokens_valid_from watermark — any JWT issued before it is rejected) for incident response; and account DEACTIVATION is enforced live (the guard re-checks is_active each request, so a disabled account's token stops working immediately rather than lasting up to 8h). (Brute-force login lockout is a tracked follow-on.)","Prev","Automated","Continuous","Eng Lead / Security","P11",
    "auth.service.ts revokeToken/revokeAllSessions (+ jti on issued JWTs); auth.controller.ts (auth/logout revokes jti, auth/users/:username/revoke-sessions); common/guards.ts (jti-denylist + is_active + tokens_valid_from checks); schema/users.ts revoked_tokens + users.tokens_valid_from + migration 0144; cutover/compliance.ts (ToE)","Inspect the jti-denylist + revoke-all watermark + the guard's per-request revocation/deactivation checks.","Re-perform: log in, logout → the token is rejected (TOKEN_REVOKED); deactivate an account → its existing token is rejected (USER_DEACTIVATED); revoke-all → pre-existing tokens rejected (re-performed by the harness).","Revocation denylist + SoD/deactivation test","Implemented")
add("ITGC-AC-16","ITGC · Access","ITGC","All","The primary financial audit trail is append-only but not tamper-EVIDENT — immutability is enforced only by a DB trigger it shares a trust boundary with, so a superuser (or out-of-band DB access) bypassing the trigger could alter/delete history undetectably.","Completeness/Integrity",
    "Audit hash chain (tamper-evidence): every audit_log row carries a per-(tenant) monotonic seq + prev_hash + hash, each hash binding the previous hash + the row's content (actor/tenant/action/ip/request_id/status/meta) — exactly the pos_journal (ITGC-AC-11) construction. The append is serialised by a FOR UPDATE lock on the latest row so concurrent writes can't fork the chain. Re-walking the chain (GET /api/admin/audit/verify, gated by 'users', RLS-scoped) recomputes every hash and reports the first row where the sequence gaps or a hash mismatches — so ANY edit/delete/insert of a past row (even one that bypassed the append-only trigger) is DETECTED. Complements ITGC-AC-10 (immutability) with detectability.","Det","Automated","Continuous / on verify","Eng Lead / Security","P13/P16",
    "common/audit.interceptor.ts (auditRowHash + per-tenant FOR UPDATE chain append); audit-viewer.service.ts verifyChain + audit-viewer.controller.ts (GET /api/admin/audit/verify); schema/system.ts audit_log.seq/prev_hash/hash + migration 0148; cutover/compliance.ts (ToE)","Inspect the chain construction (seq + prev_hash + content hash, FOR UPDATE serialisation) + the verify walk.","Re-perform: verify returns ok over the accumulated chain; then alter a past row behind a DISABLEd append-only trigger and re-verify → ok=false with a hash mismatch at the tampered seq (re-performed by the harness).","Chain verify (intact + tamper-detected) test","Implemented")

